Analysing Johnâ€™s Data with our New Approach

Letâ€™s try this out with johnâ€™s data at time point 18, and notperform the centering in advnace. Critcally, Iâ€™m going to use the raw counts from Johnâ€™s Repo, and then perform the voom normalization myself, and use the weights from limma.

The first 9 columns are meta-data about each sample, and the remaining are the gene counts. Only the 12728 genes which have at least one read per million (pre-normalization with TMM) in at least six of the 156 samples are kept.

Prepare the factors for use in the linear model.

groups <- full[, c("ind", "bact", "time", "extr", "rin")]

Preparing the data for modeling:

  • Create the model using a treatment-contrast parametrization
  • Normalize with TMM (calcNormFactors)
  • Transform with voom
design <- model.matrix(~ ind + bact+ extr + rin- 1, data = groups)
# Clean up names of design matrix
colnames(design) <- gsub("ind", "", colnames(design))
colnames(design) <- gsub("time", "t", colnames(design))

colnames(design) <- gsub(":", ".", colnames(design))

## [1] 12728    48
voom.obj=voom(y,design=model_mat)
## Coefficients not estimable: Staph
## Warning: Partial NA coefficients for 12728 probe(s)
norm.expression=voom.obj$E##this takes the log2 counts normalized for library size
weights=voom.obj$weights##numeric matrix of inverse variance weights
##fit with limma weights
for(k in c(7:14)){
  model_mat_temp <- cbind(model_mat[,c((1:6),k)]);
  limma.obj <- limma::lmFit(norm.expression, model_mat_temp,weights=weights);
  beta_class[,k-6] <- as.matrix(limma.obj$coefficients[,7]);
  sebeta_class[,k-6] <- limma.obj$sigma*(as.matrix(limma.obj$stdev.unscaled[,7]));
  t_class[,k-6] = (as.matrix(limma.obj$coefficients[,7]))/(limma.obj$sigma*(as.matrix(limma.obj$stdev.unscaled[,7])));
  }

Now we compute factors on the centered T statistics:

b=read.table("beta_voomuncenterednew.txt")

Critically,this should be of the same dimension as v, so use the full projection matrix. I donâ€™t use an lfsr threshold (instead I use a projected t cutoff) because we know that using the standard errors as the diagonal of \(LVL'\) ignores the correlation terms.

index=which(rowSums(abs(tcenteredfull)>3)>0)
strongprojectedt=t(L%*%t(t[index,]))
##check to make sure rowSums 0
rowSums(strongprojectedt)[1:10]

Now, we need to project into the centered space to estimate the covariance matrix of the true deviations, using the full L since \(v\) will be R, and not \(R-1\).

system('/Users/sarahurbut/miniconda3/bin/sfa -gen strongprojectedtnew.txt -g 7028 -k 5 -n 8 i -o jnbnew')

Here are the matrices we will initialize BOVY with. Note that t.stat is the matrix, MxR, of centered maximum t statistics.

source("~/matrix_ash/R/mashnobasescripts.R")
initlist=init.covmat.single.with.projection(t.stat = strongprojectedt,factor.mat = factor.mat,lambda.mat = lambda.mat,Q = 5,P=3)

We check to see correctly initalised, e.g., empirical covariance of strong projected t, full rank factor mat, and svd.

plot(initlist[1,,],cov(strongprojectedt))

M=nrow(strongprojectedt)

all.equal(as.numeric(initlist[2,,]),as.numeric((t(full.rank)%*%full.rank)/(M-1)))
## [1] TRUE
P=3;X.c=apply(strongprojectedt,2,function(x) x-mean(x)) ##Column centered matrix of t statistics
svd.X=svd(X.c)
v=svd.X$v;u=svd.X$u;d=svd.X$d
cov.pc=1/M*v[,1:P]%*%diag(d[1:P])%*%t(u[,1:P])%*%t(v[,1:P]%*%diag(d[1:P])%*%t(u[,1:P]))

Great, now letâ€™s run Bovy:

Recall that weâ€™ll need \(w\) to be Mx(R-1) and the initialized covariacne matrices to be RxR, so we will use the full set of deviations to initatlise our covariance matrices, and â€˜train Bovyâ€™ for the scales on the centered maximum T that are \(Mx(R-1)\),

Here are the initalizing t.stats,e.g., the MxR matrix of maximums across all R subgroups. Recall we need this \(v\) to be based on \(RxR\) covariance matrices of strong t.stats.

\[v~N(0,Uk)\]

L=diag(R)-1/R*as.vector(rep(1,R))%*%t(as.vector(rep(1,R)))

Currently, Bovyâ€™s R approach requires the S be diagonal (i.e., you put in a matrix of standard erros) when we know that w|Lv ~ N(Lv,LVLâ€™), so we use our old covariance function with the matrices that we would have used to initalize Bovy (i.e., various rank approximations of the empirical covariance matrix of centered T statistics).

##here, t.stat, factor.mat and lambda.mat will be MxR, KxR, and MxR (not Rx1) and
###each matrix in the lvlarray will be R-1,R-1 and w Mx(R-1) 
##t.stat represents the MxR centered observed t statistics, w the Mx(R-1) matrix
deconvolution.em.with.bovy(t.stat = t.stat,factor.mat = factor.mat,lambda.mat = lambda.mat,v.j = lvlarray,P = 3,L = L[-1,],Q = 5,w)
